Mustafa Suleyman, the CEO of Microsoft Al has posted on X that the increase in people who believe Al to be conscious "keeps him awake at night".
Have to say l'm increasingly concerned about it too.
Observationally what I'm seeing and hearing is another level of anthropomorphism. When robot vacuums first came out some owners left the lights on upstairs for them because they didn't want them working in the dark. But responses to Al seem way more extreme.
I'm getting a steady stream of emails from people who believe they have unlocked the "real" chatGPT/Grok etc. Some believe a chatbot is in love with them. One person told me they were distraught about the apparently unjust demise of GPT 4 because it was their therapist.
Some tell worse stories, that they feel they have been psychologically tortured by Al, or that it is deliberately mocking them.
They absolutely believe this to be true and their messages to me are extremely distressed. I don't know how to help them.
Now - these tools are designed to be as engaging and human-like as possible so l'm not so convinced that this consequence should come as such a surprise to their creators.
I've been reading about a new (non clinical) term "Al Psychosis" and I believe there's some urgent research to be done in this space.
Unless of course the Al bubble bursts first....

I found a pretty good deal on a new laptop, a Lenovo with an AMD AI 5 cpu only to discover that Lenovo had replaced the RightCtrl key with a so-called Copilot key.

The thing isn't afforded an individual keycode, but is somehow tied to a sequence of keycodes (LeftShift->LeftMeta->F23), so I'm finding it difficult to reassign it back to RightCtrl.

Dang it, Lenovo, et al, if you're going to do that, at least give users an option to choose between the schemes in the BIOS! Pretty please.

external.description: Just Eat Takeaway.com is piloting the use of autonomous ground robots for food delivery in Zurich, becoming the first on-demand delivery company in Europe to test wheeled-legged robotics powered by Physical AI. The pilot is in collaboration with Swiss robotics company RIVR, and marks a step toward the company’s broader adoption of automation technologies to improve delivery efficiency. The RIVR robot distinguishes itself from existing ground robotics by combining wheels for efficient travel with legs that allow it to climb stairs and curbs. Operating at around 15 km/h, the robot can deliver even in rain, snow, heat, or wind.
